{"completedAt":"2026-03-14T19:17:40.933Z","ok":true,"requestId":"orchestrate_testing_1773515860899_1","result":{"plan":{"objective":"Perform an autonomous environment bootstrap test for the Jungle application without explicit URL.","rationale":"The test aims to ensure that the Jungle application can be started and is functioning correctly in a local environment, validating its UI components and responsiveness, especially under conditions where the application might not be running initially.","app_bootstrap":{"required":true,"reason":"The application may not be running, and we need to ensure it is started correctly for testing.","workspace":"C:\\Users\\William\\Desktop\\Projects\\Genai_2026","files":[{"path":".env","content":""}],"install_command":"npm install","start_command":"npm start","startup_timeout_ms":30000},"steps":[{"action":"goto","target":"http://localhost:3000"},{"action":"wait","target":10000},{"action":"assertVisible","target":"text=Jungle"},{"action":"screenshot","target":"final_screenshot.png"}],"assertions":["The Jungle application is visible and loaded successfully.","The main title 'Jungle' is displayed on the page."],"success_criteria":["The application starts without errors.","The main UI elements are visible and interactable.","The application responds correctly after the wait period."]},"execution":{"status":"fail","summary":"locator.waitFor: Timeout 10000ms exceeded.\nCall log:\n\u001b[2m  - waiting for locator('text=Jungle').first() to be visible\u001b[22m\n","steps":[],"video_path":"C:\\Users\\William\\Desktop\\Projects\\Genai_2026\\db\\langflow_agentic_runs\\run_6920_1773515875993\\2af9f5776fba8b1aab2f22f73ef77427.webm","artifacts":["C:\\Users\\William\\Desktop\\Projects\\Genai_2026\\db\\langflow_agentic_runs\\run_6920_1773515875993\\2af9f5776fba8b1aab2f22f73ef77427.webm","C:\\Users\\William\\Desktop\\Projects\\Genai_2026\\db\\langflow_agentic_runs\\run_6920_1773515875993\\final_1773515896389.png","C:\\Users\\William\\Desktop\\Projects\\Genai_2026\\db\\langflow_agentic_runs\\run_6920_1773515875993\\playwright_executor.generated.js","C:\\Users\\William\\Desktop\\Projects\\Genai_2026\\db\\langflow_agentic_runs\\run_6920_1773515875993\\request_parser.json"],"generated_code_path":"C:\\Users\\William\\Desktop\\Projects\\Genai_2026\\db\\langflow_agentic_runs\\run_6920_1773515875993\\playwright_executor.generated.js","parser_path":"C:\\Users\\William\\Desktop\\Projects\\Genai_2026\\db\\langflow_agentic_runs\\run_6920_1773515875993\\request_parser.json","stdout":"{\"status\":\"fail\",\"summary\":\"locator.waitFor: Timeout 10000ms exceeded.\\nCall log:\\n\\u001b[2m  - waiting for locator('text=Jungle').first() to be visible\\u001b[22m\\n\",\"steps\":[],\"video_path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\William\\\\Desktop\\\\Projects\\\\Genai_2026\\\\db\\\\langflow_agentic_runs\\\\run_6920_1773515875993\\\\2af9f5776fba8b1aab2f22f73ef77427.webm\",\"artifacts\":[\"C:\\\\Users\\\\William\\\\Desktop\\\\Projects\\\\Genai_2026\\\\db\\\\langflow_agentic_runs\\\\run_6920_1773515875993\\\\2af9f5776fba8b1aab2f22f73ef77427.webm\",\"C:\\\\Users\\\\William\\\\Desktop\\\\Projects\\\\Genai_2026\\\\db\\\\langflow_agentic_runs\\\\run_6920_1773515875993\\\\final_1773515896389.png\",\"C:\\\\Users\\\\William\\\\Desktop\\\\Projects\\\\Genai_2026\\\\db\\\\langflow_agentic_runs\\\\run_6920_1773515875993\\\\playwright_executor.generated.js\",\"C:\\\\Users\\\\William\\\\Desktop\\\\Projects\\\\Genai_2026\\\\db\\\\langflow_agentic_runs\\\\run_6920_1773515875993\\\\request_parser.json\"]}","stderr":"","app_runtime":{"status":"already_running","target_url":"http://localhost:3000","ready":true,"started_by_orchestrator":false,"workspace":"C:\\Users\\William\\Desktop\\Projects\\Genai_2026","start_command":"","install_command":"","log_path":null,"pid":null,"error_message":""}},"critique":{"verdict":"fail","overall_severity":10,"summary":"The application experiences a catastrophic render failure, immediately displaying a raw, unstyled 'Cannot GET /' server error. This is the most severe class of defect, as no part of the user interface loads. The transition is instantaneous, providing no loading feedback, which is perceptually jarring and feels like a system crash. The resulting error screen is static and unhelpful, offering no guidance or recovery options.","defects":[{"id":"catastrophic_render_failure","severity_0_10":10,"description":"The application completely fails to render any UI components, instead displaying a raw server error message ('Cannot GET /'). This indicates a fundamental failure in the application's bootstrapping or routing process, making the entire product unusable.","evidence":"The entire video, from the first frame, shows a blank white screen with the unstyled text 'Cannot GET /' in the top-left corner.","recommendation":"Investigate and resolve the root cause of the server-side or client-side routing failure. This may involve fixing a broken API endpoint, correcting application configuration, or addressing an issue in the initial JavaScript execution that prevents the UI from mounting."},{"id":"abrupt_state_transition","severity_0_10":9,"description":"The application state transitions instantaneously from a pre-load blank screen to the raw error message in a single frame. This complete lack of a loading state or animated transition is a critical failure in motion readability, creating a jarring, disorienting experience for the user that mimics a crash.","evidence":"The video begins with the error message already present. There is no observable loading sequence, spinner, or skeleton screen, indicating an instantaneous change.","recommendation":"Implement a managed loading sequence. On navigation, immediately render a loading skeleton or branded animation with a gentle `ease-in` curve over ~200ms. If an error occurs, this loading state should gracefully transition (e.g., cross-fade over ~300ms) to a styled error component, clearly communicating the state change from 'loading' to 'error'."},{"id":"static_unhelpful_error_state","severity_0_10":7,"description":"The error screen is completely static, unstyled, and uninformative. It lacks any 'living' element to reassure the user the application hasn't frozen, and provides no interactive elements for recovery (e.g., 'Retry' or 'Go Home'). From a physics perspective, the UI has zero energy, feeling dead and unresponsive.","evidence":"The screen remains frozen on the plain text error message for the entire duration of the video, with no animations or interactive cues.","recommendation":"Replace the raw text with a user-friendly, styled error component. This component should include: 1) A clear, helpful message explaining the issue. 2) An animated icon (e.g., a pulsing warning sign) to indicate a managed, responsive state. 3) Interactive buttons like 'Retry' or 'Go Home' with subtle hover/focus animations to provide the user a path forward."}],"strengths":["Video artifact captured with sufficient size for review.","Plan includes passive observation window, which successfully captured the failure state."],"recommendations":["Prioritize fixing the root cause of the catastrophic render failure to make the application usable.","Implement a global state management strategy that includes distinct, user-visible states for loading, success, and error conditions.","Design and build a comprehensive, user-friendly error component that can be used application-wide for graceful error handling.","Ensure all major state transitions have a minimum perceptible duration (e.g., >150ms) and use appropriate easing curves to guide the user's attention and prevent jarring visual changes."],"source":"gemini_chain_video","critic_chain":{"video":{"video_input_used":true,"video_reason":"inline_video_attached","video_bytes":52713},"detailed_text":"As a strict animation and physics QA critic, I have reviewed the provided video. The fundamental issue is a catastrophic failure to render any UI, which in itself is the most severe form of animation and UX defect. My critique will focus on the presentation of this failure state.\n\nHere is my comprehensive, technical analysis.\n\n***\n\n### 1) Abrupt State Transition and Lack of Feedback\n**What happens**\nUpon navigation, the application state transitions instantaneously from a pre-load blank screen to a raw, unstyled \"Cannot GET /\" error message. This change occurs in a single frame, with no intermediate loading or feedback states.\n\n**Why it looks wrong**\nThis is a critical failure in motion readability. The user is given no information about the application's lifecycle. The transition is not an animation; it is a teleportation. In physics-based animation, objects do not instantaneously appear. They must travel through space over time. This instantaneous state change is perceptually jarring and feels like a system crash, not a managed application state. It exhibits infinite energy volatility, moving from a zero-energy state to a final error state with no observable kinetic phase (the loading process). This breaks the user's mental model of how a digital service should operate.\n\n**Fix**\nImplement a managed loading sequence to communicate the application's status.\n- **Initial State:** On navigation, immediately render a loading skeleton or a branded loading animation. This animation should have a gentle `ease-in` curve (e.g., `cubic-bezier(0.4, 0, 0.2, 1)`) over ~200ms to signal the start of a process.\n- **Error State Transition:** If an unrecoverable error occurs, the loading animation must gracefully transition to a styled, user-friendly error component. This should be a cross-fade or a similar transition over ~300ms. This animated transition clearly communicates the change of state from \"loading\" to \"error\" and gives the user time to process the information, preventing the disorienting \"pop-in\" effect.\n\n### 2) Perceptual Tunneling on Render Failure\n**What happens**\nThe user's experience \"tunnels\" directly from the intent to load the application to the final failure state. All intermediate steps of the application bootstrapping (e.g., fetching data, rendering components) are visually absent.\n\n**Why it looks wrong**\nThis is a form of frame-rate clipping or tunneling, but applied to the user experience journey rather than a single moving object. The user is not guided through the application's process; they are dropped at the end of a failed one. A well-designed interface uses motion to tell a story and guide the user's focus. By rendering the error in a single frame, you are skipping every chapter of that story. This makes the UI feel unpredictable and broken, as the cause (the failed process) is disconnected from the effect (the error message).\n\n**Fix**\nEnsure all major state transitions have a minimum perceptible duration.\n- **Minimum Duration:** No major UI state change should complete in less than 100ms. For a critical failure like this, the transition from the loading state to the error state should be explicitly timed (e.g., 250-400ms).\n- **Easing:** The transition should use an easing curve that respects perceptual momentum. An `ease-out` curve should be used for the error message appearing, making it feel like it's smoothly arriving at its final, static state rather than crashing into view.\n\n### 3) Zero-Energy Static Error State\n**What happens**\nThe error screen itself is completely static. The plain text remains frozen on the screen, providing no indication that the application is still running or responsive.\n\n**Why it looks wrong**\nA completely static UI, especially an error screen, feels dead. It lacks any \"living\" element to reassure the user that the application hasn't completely frozen. From a physics perspective, the UI has zero energy and zero momentum, which is visually uninteresting and uninformative. Good UI design often incorporates subtle, ambient motion to create a sense of responsiveness and polish. This screen has none.\n\n**Fix**\nIntroduce subtle, low-energy, ambient animations to the error page to indicate the application is in a managed, responsive state.\n- **Animated Icon:** Replace the raw text with a properly designed error component that includes an animated icon (e.g., a warning sign that subtly pulses or an 'X' that draws itself once).\n- **Interactive Element Cues:** Include a \"Retry\" or \"Go Home\" button. This button should have a subtle animated cue on a loop, such as a soft glow or shimmer, to draw the user's attention and signify interactivity. This gives the user a path forward and shows the application can still accept input.\n- **Background Motion:** A subtle, generative, and non-distracting animated background (e.g., a very slow-moving gradient or particle field) can keep the screen from feeling inert without overwhelming the user.","severity":{"overall_severity":10,"severity_reasoning":"The critique identifies a 'catastrophic failure to render any UI,' which is described as the most severe form of animation and UX defect. The instantaneous transition to a raw error message is perceptually jarring, breaks the user's mental model, and mimics a system crash rather than a managed application state. This complete lack of feedback and graceful error handling constitutes a critical failure.","top_risks":["Abrupt State Transition and Lack of Feedback: The instantaneous jump to a raw error message is jarring and provides no information about the application's lifecycle.","Perceptual Tunneling on Render Failure: The user is dropped directly into the final error state, skipping all intermediate loading steps and making the UI feel broken and unpredictable.","Zero-Energy Static Error State: The error screen is completely static, feeling 'dead' and providing no reassurance, user guidance, or path to recovery."],"verdict":"fail"},"raw_model_outputs":{"stage1_text":"As a strict animation and physics QA critic, I have reviewed the provided video. The fundamental issue is a catastrophic failure to render any UI, which in itself is the most severe form of animation and UX defect. My critique will focus on the presentation of this failure state.\n\nHere is my comprehensive, technical analysis.\n\n***\n\n### 1) Abrupt State Transition and Lack of Feedback\n**What happens**\nUpon navigation, the application state transitions instantaneously from a pre-load blank screen to a raw, unstyled \"Cannot GET /\" error message. This change occurs in a single frame, with no intermediate loading or feedback states.\n\n**Why it looks wrong**\nThis is a critical failure in motion readability. The user is given no information about the application's lifecycle. The transition is not an animation; it is a teleportation. In physics-based animation, objects do not instantaneously appear. They must travel through space over time. This instantaneous state change is perceptually jarring and feels like a system crash, not a managed application state. It exhibits infinite energy volatility, moving from a zero-energy state to a final error state with no observable kinetic phase (the loading process). This breaks the user's mental model of how a digital service should operate.\n\n**Fix**\nImplement a managed loading sequence to communicate the application's status.\n- **Initial State:** On navigation, immediately render a loading skeleton or a branded loading animation. This animation should have a gentle `ease-in` curve (e.g., `cubic-bezier(0.4, 0, 0.2, 1)`) over ~200ms to signal the start of a process.\n- **Error State Transition:** If an unrecoverable error occurs, the loading animation must gracefully transition to a styled, user-friendly error component. This should be a cross-fade or a similar transition over ~300ms. This animated transition clearly communicates the change of state from \"loading\" to \"error\" and gives the user time to process the information, preventing the disorienting \"pop-in\" effect.\n\n### 2) Perceptual Tunneling on Render Failure\n**What happens**\nThe user's experience \"tunnels\" directly from the intent to load the application to the final failure state. All intermediate steps of the application bootstrapping (e.g., fetching data, rendering components) are visually absent.\n\n**Why it looks wrong**\nThis is a form of frame-rate clipping or tunneling, but applied to the user experience journey rather than a single moving object. The user is not guided through the application's process; they are dropped at the end of a failed one. A well-designed interface uses motion to tell a story and guide the user's focus. By rendering the error in a single frame, you are skipping every chapter of that story. This makes the UI feel unpredictable and broken, as the cause (the failed process) is disconnected from the effect (the error message).\n\n**Fix**\nEnsure all major state transitions have a minimum perceptible duration.\n- **Minimum Duration:** No major UI state change should complete in less than 100ms. For a critical failure like this, the transition from the loading state to the error state should be explicitly timed (e.g., 250-400ms).\n- **Easing:** The transition should use an easing curve that respects perceptual momentum. An `ease-out` curve should be used for the error message appearing, making it feel like it's smoothly arriving at its final, static state rather than crashing into view.\n\n### 3) Zero-Energy Static Error State\n**What happens**\nThe error screen itself is completely static. The plain text remains frozen on the screen, providing no indication that the application is still running or responsive.\n\n**Why it looks wrong**\nA completely static UI, especially an error screen, feels dead. It lacks any \"living\" element to reassure the user that the application hasn't completely frozen. From a physics perspective, the UI has zero energy and zero momentum, which is visually uninteresting and uninformative. Good UI design often incorporates subtle, ambient motion to create a sense of responsiveness and polish. This screen has none.\n\n**Fix**\nIntroduce subtle, low-energy, ambient animations to the error page to indicate the application is in a managed, responsive state.\n- **Animated Icon:** Replace the raw text with a properly designed error component that includes an animated icon (e.g., a warning sign that subtly pulses or an 'X' that draws itself once).\n- **Interactive Element Cues:** Include a \"Retry\" or \"Go Home\" button. This button should have a subtle animated cue on a loop, such as a soft glow or shimmer, to draw the user's attention and signify interactivity. This gives the user a path forward and shows the application can still accept input.\n- **Background Motion:** A subtle, generative, and non-distracting animated background (e.g., a very slow-moving gradient or particle field) can keep the screen from feeling inert without overwhelming the user.","stage2_text":"```json\n{\n  \"overall_severity\": 10,\n  \"severity_reasoning\": \"The critique identifies a 'catastrophic failure to render any UI,' which is described as the most severe form of animation and UX defect. The instantaneous transition to a raw error message is perceptually jarring, breaks the user's mental model, and mimics a system crash rather than a managed application state. This complete lack of feedback and graceful error handling constitutes a critical failure.\",\n  \"top_risks\": [\n    \"Abrupt State Transition and Lack of Feedback: The instantaneous jump to a raw error message is jarring and provides no information about the application's lifecycle.\",\n    \"Perceptual Tunneling on Render Failure: The user is dropped directly into the final error state, skipping all intermediate loading steps and making the UI feel broken and unpredictable.\",\n    \"Zero-Energy Static Error State: The error screen is completely static, feeling 'dead' and providing no reassurance, user guidance, or path to recovery.\"\n  ],\n  \"verdict\": \"fail\"\n}\n```","stage3_text":"```json\n{\n  \"verdict\": \"fail\",\n  \"overall_severity\": 10,\n  \"summary\": \"The application experiences a catastrophic render failure, immediately displaying a raw, unstyled 'Cannot GET /' server error. This is the most severe class of defect, as no part of the user interface loads. The transition is instantaneous, providing no loading feedback, which is perceptually jarring and feels like a system crash. The resulting error screen is static and unhelpful, offering no guidance or recovery options.\",\n  \"defects\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"catastrophic_render_failure\",\n      \"severity_0_10\": 10,\n      \"description\": \"The application completely fails to render any UI components, instead displaying a raw server error message ('Cannot GET /'). This indicates a fundamental failure in the application's bootstrapping or routing process, making the entire product unusable.\",\n      \"evidence\": \"The entire video, from the first frame, shows a blank white screen with the unstyled text 'Cannot GET /' in the top-left corner.\",\n      \"recommendation\": \"Investigate and resolve the root cause of the server-side or client-side routing failure. This may involve fixing a broken API endpoint, correcting application configuration, or addressing an issue in the initial JavaScript execution that prevents the UI from mounting.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"abrupt_state_transition\",\n      \"severity_0_10\": 9,\n      \"description\": \"The application state transitions instantaneously from a pre-load blank screen to the raw error message in a single frame. This complete lack of a loading state or animated transition is a critical failure in motion readability, creating a jarring, disorienting experience for the user that mimics a crash.\",\n      \"evidence\": \"The video begins with the error message already present. There is no observable loading sequence, spinner, or skeleton screen, indicating an instantaneous change.\",\n      \"recommendation\": \"Implement a managed loading sequence. On navigation, immediately render a loading skeleton or branded animation with a gentle `ease-in` curve over ~200ms. If an error occurs, this loading state should gracefully transition (e.g., cross-fade over ~300ms) to a styled error component, clearly communicating the state change from 'loading' to 'error'.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"static_unhelpful_error_state\",\n      \"severity_0_10\": 7,\n      \"description\": \"The error screen is completely static, unstyled, and uninformative. It lacks any 'living' element to reassure the user the application hasn't frozen, and provides no interactive elements for recovery (e.g., 'Retry' or 'Go Home'). From a physics perspective, the UI has zero energy, feeling dead and unresponsive.\",\n      \"evidence\": \"The screen remains frozen on the plain text error message for the entire duration of the video, with no animations or interactive cues.\",\n      \"recommendation\": \"Replace the raw text with a user-friendly, styled error component. This component should include: 1) A clear, helpful message explaining the issue. 2) An animated icon (e.g., a pulsing warning sign) to indicate a managed, responsive state. 3) Interactive buttons like 'Retry' or 'Go Home' with subtle hover/focus animations to provide the user a path forward.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"strengths\": [\n    \"Video artifact captured with sufficient size for review.\",\n    \"Plan includes passive observation window, which successfully captured the failure state.\"\n  ],\n  \"recommendations\": [\n    \"Prioritize fixing the root cause of the catastrophic render failure to make the application usable.\",\n    \"Implement a global state management strategy that includes distinct, user-visible states for loading, success, and error conditions.\",\n    \"Design and build a comprehensive, user-friendly error component that can be used application-wide for graceful error handling.\",\n    \"Ensure all major state transitions have a minimum perceptible duration (e.g., >150ms) and use appropriate easing curves to guide the user's attention and prevent jarring visual changes.\"\n  ],\n  \"score_breakdown\": {\n    \"physics_consistency\": 0,\n    \"collision_stability\": 0,\n    \"motion_readability\": 0,\n    \"temporal_smoothness\": 0\n  }\n}\n```"},"raw_model_diagnostics":{"stage1":{"ok":true,"status_code":200},"stage2":{"ok":true,"status_code":200},"stage3":{"ok":true,"status_code":200}}},"score_breakdown":{"physics_consistency":0,"collision_stability":0,"motion_readability":0,"temporal_smoothness":0}},"final_verdict":"fail","escalated":true,"severity_threshold":8,"pass_condition":"execution.status == pass AND critique.overall_severity <= 8.0"}}
